      <block class="full_text">
        <p>J. Terrence Lanni, chairman and chief executive of MGM Mirage, has rung up big travel bills on the shareholders' tab in recent years. Perhaps that will change once his $8.7 million condominium in the company's CityCenter development in downtown Las Vegas is ready.</p>
        <p>According to the casino operator's proxy statement, Mr. Lanni and the controlling shareholder, Kirk Kerkorian, put down 10 percent deposits in January on CityCenter apartments with price tags of more than $8.6 million each.</p>
        <p>Last year, the company spent about $250,000 on Mr. Lanni's personal use of company planes. That was less than half the cost of his jet travel in each of the three previous years.</p>
        <p>PATRICK McGEEHAN</p>
        <p>OPENERS: SUITS</p>
